			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The other thing dictating palette assignment is CHR ROM/RAM address space limit. If you are dynamically loading tiles into CHR RAM or swapping 1K (64-tile) chunks of VRAM using an MMC3-class mapper depending on what tile is visible, that may provide an additional constraint on what enemy combinations are viable.<br /><br />$1000-$13FF and $3F11-$3F13: Player 1<br />$1400-$17FF and $3F15-$3F17: Player 2<br />$1800-$1BFF and $3F19-$3F1B: Enemy 1<br />$1C00-$1FFF and $3F1D-$3F1F: Enemy 2<br /><br />How are you organizing CHR memory? What mapper, and ROM or RAM?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Gilbert wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The SMS has only one single palette for sprites, and no sprite flipping feature too, forcing you to use different sprites for even just palette swapped objects and characters facing different directions.</div><br />Because it has no hardware flipping, a Master System or Game Gear game needs to use a lookup table to flip sprite tiles. But if you do that, you can make additional lookup tables with horizontal shrinking baked in, giving you <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?f=22&amp;t=12055" class="postlink">Neo Geo-style shrinking for free</a>. (Z80 excels with page-sized LUTs.)</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
